Even when retracted the stick is long and metal‐shafted, making it noticeably heavier and giving it a large rotational inertia; the center of mass is far from the grip, so starts/stops feel sluggish compared with a small, light salt shaker.
Full can (~350 g) is a rigid cylinder but roughly twice the mass of a typical salt shaker, so the wrist feels extra momentum; still light enough to move quickly, but weight difference is noticeable.

Compact metal/plastic body likely ~100 g—close to a shaker’s mass. Center of mass is within the grip so it stops/starts readily; only drawback is non-cylindrical shape, but inertial feel is fairly convincing.

Very light mass with free particles inside gives minimal inertia and audible rattle similar to salt. Flexible bag and wide shape differ from a rigid shaker, but the light stop/start dynamics are appropriate.
The monitor-on-stand assembly is extremely heavy and effectively immobile; inertia is orders of magnitude above that of a salt shaker.
Bulky (~700 g) and wide; requires two hands or large grip, with substantial inertia—feels nothing like a light shaker.
Mouse mass ~100 g and small size allow quick wrist flicks with little momentum; center of mass near grip. Shape is flatter than a shaker but inertial feel is fairly similar.
Extremely light (~10 g) so inertia is even less than expected; thin form factor also changes grip, making weight feel insubstantial.
Ceramic pot with soil is heavy and slightly top-heavy; takes effort to start/stop, overshooting expected momentum for a salt shaker.
Mass is moderate but distributed high above the pinch point, creating more rotational inertia; fragility also discourages rapid shaking.
Controller weighs ~200-250 g and is bulkier; inertia is higher and the asymmetric grip shifts the center of mass away from a small shaker feel.
Armrest is attached to a multi-kilogram chair; cannot replicate light, rapidly responsive inertia.
Desk is effectively immovable by wrist flicks; inertia is vastly greater than required.
Filled bottle (~300 g) is heavier and taller; liquid sloshes causing delayed stops, so overall momentum exceeds that of a salt shaker.
Very light (~25 g) so minimal inertia matches expectation, but soft compressible body and flat shape deviate from rigid shaker feel.
Metal scissors have higher mass and uneven weight distribution with blades extending forward, yielding more rotational inertia than desired.
Bulky object requires two-handed grip; although light for its size, its volume and air drag make quick, crisp starts/stops impossible.
Dense metal (~500 g) in a small form factor feels far heavier than a salt shaker; high inertia and strong downward pull are obvious on the first shake.
Long handle and bristle mass shift weight away from grip point; rotational inertia and air drag of bristles hinder the snappy movement expected.
Large furniture piece; effectively immovable with wrist flicks, providing no similarity to a small light shaker.
Table mass is far greater than a salt shaker; cannot simulate quick starts/stops or light inertia.
Bench is heavy and fixed; any attempted shake encounters large inertia, utterly unlike a light shaker.
Umbrella is long and moderately heavy; mass distributed along shaft increases moment of inertia, preventing instantaneous stops.
Large, floppy, and heavy; cannot be shaken rapidly with one hand, offering none of the desired light, crisp inertial response.

The foam handle is cylindrical and near hand-grip diameter, but the length is 4–5× that of a salt shaker, forcing an elongated grasp that never lets the fingers feel a closed 4 cm outline. Mass distribution is also very different.

Aluminum can provides a rigid, smooth cylinder that the fingers can wrap around. Diameter (~6.5 cm) is larger and height (~12 cm) is taller than the 4 cm, squat shaker, so grip feels slightly spread and top never reached by index pad, but overall cylindrical outline is reasonably similar.
Stapler is a blocky, irregular form with flat sides and a gaping jaw; cannot achieve a comfortable small power-grip cylinder feel. Outline and contact cues diverge strongly from a shaker.
Soft, flexible pouch with no fixed diameter; fingers squeeze a deformable surface, so the rigid cylindrical outline is entirely absent.
A thin flat lip—nothing like a small cylinder; impossible to wrap the hand around a 4 cm diameter shape.
Large rectangular slab with keys; no cylindrical body to grip.
Low curved dome fits under palm but has oval footprint; fingers rest on top rather than wrap around a round wall. Some curvature exists, yet outline mismatch dominates.
Rigid cylinder but diameter ≈1 cm and length >14 cm—grip becomes a fingertip pinch or pencil grasp, not the short 4 cm diameter power grip.
Ceramic pot is rigid and roughly cylindrical with vertical flutes, but its diameter (~8 cm) and height exceed the intended shaker, and the plant protrusion prevents full wrap-around grip.
If gripped by the stem it is far thinner; if gripped by the bowl it is much larger and spherical. Neither grip matches a 4 cm squat cylinder.
Controller horn is asymmetrical and contoured, closer to a pistol grip than a symmetric cylinder. Diameter varies and fingers don’t make a closed ring.
Flat, wide armrest—no cylindrical outline, far too large to enclose with hand.
Straight, broad plank; user cannot form a cylindrical grip or feel a 4 cm diameter.
Mid-section of bottle is cylindrical and graspable, but diameter (~6 cm) and height are larger; taper toward neck disrupts uniform outline and trigger protrusion interferes with full wrap.
Soft rectangular prism, easily compressed; offers no rigid circular outline.
Irregular L-shaped handle loops with gaps; cannot simulate small uniform cylinder.
Very large, soft, hemispherical cushion—diameter and firmness completely wrong.

Short steel cylinder about the right diameter; top knob gives orientation cue like shaker cap. However it is extremely heavy (500 g) and fully smooth, so weight and faceted body mismatch the expected light glass shaker.
Handle is rectangular/flat and elongated; bristles extend to one side, preventing a symmetric cylindrical feel.
Large, soft planar cushion; impossible to grasp as a 4 cm rigid cylinder.
Broad flat board; no cylindrical contour for the hand.
Armrest is wide and flattened oval, far larger than hand can enclose.
Handle is rigid but J-shaped; straight section diameter ~1.5 cm and length long. Curved hook breaks the continuous short cylinder feel.
Very large, soft, amorphous; no match to small rigid cylindrical shaker outline.

physicalObject: telescoping selfie stick with black handle and phone mount
explanation: The selfie-stick can be gripped at the handle while the telescoping shaft or phone clamp is twisted, giving some friction from the telescoping joints, but rotation is not continuous around a fixed central axle and resistance is low and irregular; no gritty feedback or pepper-drop confirmation.
The can is a single rigid shell—no part can rotate relative to another, so the required twisting mechanism and resistance are completely absent.
A stapler’s top is hinged for vertical pressing, not axial rotation. Trying to twist it offers almost no travel or intended resistance, so interactivity is largely missing.
The bag can be wrung, producing some soft resistance, but the object is flexible, lacks a rigid two-piece structure, and provides no continuous rotational friction typical of a grinder.

physicalObject: iMac desktop computer with aluminum stand
explanation: The monitor can swivel slightly on its stand, giving smooth low-force friction, but size, weight, and limited angle prevent two-handed twisting like a grinder; no gritty feedback.
The keyboard is rigid; there is no part designed to rotate relative to another, so grinder-like twisting is impossible.
Mouse is a sealed shell with no rotating components; cannot reproduce twisting resistance.

The pen’s upper barrel twists relative to the lower barrel with moderate, continuous thread resistance and faint clicks; length (~14 cm) and two-hand grip mimic the knob/body interaction reasonably well, though torque is lighter and scale slightly shorter than a 17 cm grinder.

physicalObject: small succulent plant in yellow ceramic pot
explanation: Pot and soil are one rigid mass; no rotational degree of freedom exists.
The glass is monolithic; nothing rotates relative to anything else, so grinder-like feedback cannot be produced.

physicalObject: white and grey camouflage-pattern video game controller
explanation: Controller halves are fixed; only thumb-sticks and triggers move. Attempting to twist the grips yields minimal flex and no intentional rotational resistance.
Chair components are far apart and not designed for axial twisting between two hands; lacks suitable mechanism and scale is unwieldy.
A flat desk cannot be twisted; no moving parts, so interactive rotation is impossible.

physicalObject: clear plastic spray bottle with blue liquid
explanation: The nozzle head can be twisted with discernible threaded resistance and occasional clicks, but only a tiny top rotates; interaction is one-handed on a small part, lacking the full two-hand torque cycle of a grinder.

physicalObject: green and yellow kitchen scrub sponge
explanation: Soft sponge offers pliable shear when wrung, not rigid rotational resistance; no mechanical feedback.
Scissors pivot open/closed, not around a vertical axis; twisting the handles is not intended and gives negligible motion.
Plush is floppy; twisting produces soft fabric shear without any rigid resistance or clicks.
The knurled cap can be unscrewed, giving continuous thread friction similar to grinder resistance, but the object is very small (≈3 cm) so cannot be gripped two-handed, and no gritty micro-vibration.
Handle and bristle block are fixed; no axial rotation possible.
Large soft cushion cannot be rotated against itself to create grinder-like feedback.
Rigid flat surface; no movable parts, so twisting interaction is impossible.

physicalObject: blue upholstered bench with black armrests
explanation: Bench is a large fixed piece of furniture; attempting to twist armrests does not replicate grinder mechanics or resistance.

physicalObject: transparent umbrella with white curved handle
explanation: The shaft can rotate slightly within the fabric when opening/closing, giving some friction, and length allows two-hand grip; however, rotation is limited, not continuous, and resistance is low and smooth without gritty feedback.
Soft, amorphous object provides no rigid rotational components; cannot simulate grinder twisting.

physicalObject: telescoping selfie stick with black handle
explanation: Very long, thin rod shape; lacks the short, bulbous convex profile of a 5 cm-wide pepper grinder. Only the rubber end offers a cylindrical grip, but overall outline feels nothing like the desired curves.
Diameter (~6 cm) is close, and it is rigid and cylindrical, but the body is straight with flat ends—no necked-in waist or bulbous top, so convex curvature feedback is missing.
Size is much shorter and flatter; outline is more blocky with a hinge rather than smooth convex curves. Does not fill the palm like a grinder body.
Flexible, thin plastic pouch; no rigid convex shape at all—completely unlike a wooden grinder body.

physicalObject: iMac desktop computer with aluminum stand
explanation: Large, flat monitor and pedestal; impossible to grasp like a handheld grinder and offers no comparable curves.
Rectangular slab with sharp edges and wide footprint; zero similarity to a small convex cylindrical grinder.
Has a gentle dome but is very low and wide; cannot be wrapped by fingers in a vertical cylindrical grip, so the perceived outline diverges strongly.
Cylindrical but only ~1 cm in diameter and completely straight; no palm-filling convex curves or 5 cm base.

physicalObject: small succulent plant in yellow ribbed ceramic pot
explanation: Pot presents a short barrel with a slight waist and convex lower rim; diameter seems near 7 cm, height ~10 cm—closer than most objects but still stubbier and lacks distinct top knob.
Bowl offers a convex surface, but the stem creates a discontinuity and the grip orientation (sideways stem) differs from vertical grinder body.
Ergonomic winged shape for two-handed game grip, not a single convex cylinder; no similarity in outline.

physicalObject: black mesh-backed office chair with armrests
explanation: Furniture piece far larger than hand-held scale; outline and ergonomics entirely mismatched.
Large flat plane; no handheld convex contours; completely incompatible with expected outline.

physicalObject: clear plastic spray bottle with blue liquid
explanation: Overall height and body diameter appear close to a real grinder, and the bottle has a cylindrical, slightly convex body that fills the palm reasonably well. The trigger head differs from a grinder knob, but the main outline similarity is moderate.
Flat rectangular prism, compressible; provides none of the rigid convex curvature needed.
Thin intersecting arms and loops; outline is skeletal and angular, not convex cylindrical.
Large soft dome offers convexity but scale is far beyond hand size and the plush deforms, losing rigid outline fidelity.
Rigid mini-cylinder with slight domed top; shape is correct but diameter (~2.5 cm) and height are about half the required, so grip feels too small.
Long flat handle with bristles; completely lacks the bulbous grinder profile.
Furniture scale and soft planar surface; no resemblance to a handheld convex cylinder.
Large flat furniture piece; outline mismatch is absolute.
Bench is massive and rectangular; cannot replicate convex hand-sized outline.

physicalObject: transparent umbrella with white curved handle
explanation: Handle offers a short curved segment but overall object is long and narrow; no central bulbous body or 5 cm base diameter.
Provides large convex surface but is soft and room-sized; scale and rigidity differ drastically from a handheld grinder.
